Here is a refactored version of the code that uses the `sort` method to get the latest yearly data rather than using `reduce`:


```
export const getLatestYearlyData = (
 data: YearlyUserData[]
): Pick<
 YearlyUserData,
 'leaveCount' | 'personalBudget' | 'officeBudget' | 'year'
> => {
 if (data.length === 0) {
 return {
 year: new Date().getFullYear(),
 leaveCount: 0,
 personalBudget: 0,
 officeBudget: 0,
 }
 }

 data.sort((a, b) => b.year - a.year);
 return data[0];
}
```
This version of the code first sorts the `data` array in descending order by the `year` field, and then returns the first element of the array, which will be the latest year. This eliminates the need to use the `reduce` method and should be more efficient.

